

# Data Science and AIML  Portfolio

Welcome to my data science portfolio repository. This index provides a detailed, end-to-end look at my technical journey, showcasing how I solve complex business
problems using machine learning, computer vision, natural language processing, and cloud deployment.

### SuperKart Sales Forecasting and Cloud Deployment

In this project, I built a complete data science pipeline to help a retail chain predict product revenue and manage its supply chains. I started by checking the quality
of a historical dataset containing 8,763 unique item records to ensure it had no missing numbers or duplicate rows. By reviewing the statistical summaries, I found key 
baseline numbers like an average product maximum retail price of 147.03 and an average store sales total of 3,464.00. This process helped me understand how the data
was spread out and locate extreme outliers, like sudden drops in a product's shelf visibility, which needed to be cleaned before model training. To find deeper insights,
I used Python libraries to make visual charts like histograms and boxplots. These charts showed me that retail demand is heavily right-skewed, meaning a small group of
high-selling products brings in most of the company's revenue. I also used bar charts to see how different items sell depending on the tier of the city, store layout
designs, and store sizes, which taught me that an item's placement, price, and location interact to drive final sales. In the engineering stage, I built an automated
transformation pipeline that scales numeric fields and converts text categories into binary numbers, ensuring the data is ready for predictive modeling. I split the data
set into training and testing blocks and used an advanced gradient boosting algorithm called XGBoost, running an automated grid search to find the absolute best settings
. Finally, I saved the completed pipeline and deployed it to a live cloud platform using Streamlit and Hugging Face, turning my local data code into an active web 
dashboard where a retail manager can input store properties to instantly forecast product sales in real time.

### HelmNet: Computer Vision Safety Monitoring

For this project, I learned how to handle, explore, and preprocess image data to build an automated safety monitoring system named HelmNet, designed to check if workers
are wearing safety helmets to reduce head injuries. I began by working with a dataset of 4,125 total images categorized into two classes, where 3,161 images showed
individuals wearing safety helmets and 964 images showed individuals without them. In the initial data auditing phase, I used Python libraries to read and standardize
the raw images, converting them into multi-dimensional NumPy arrays with uniform dimensions of 200 pixels in height by 200 pixels in width across 3 RGB color channels.
This rigorous preprocessing step allowed me to verify that the final structural dataset shape was perfectly optimized for deep learning, creating a processed file asset
totaling 472.07 megabytes. I learned the critical importance of ensuring reproducibility in computer vision workflows by setting deterministic random seeds across the
Python environment, NumPy operations, and the TensorFlow backend, which guarantees that data splits and layer initializations remain consistent across training runs. 
This project also provided deep insights into the challenges of building image classification models for real-world industrial environments. I learned how variations 
in external conditions—such as diverse camera angles, fluctuating lighting, busy backgrounds, and different worker poses like walking, standing, or operating heavy 
machinery—impact a model's ability to extract meaningful features. A major technical takeaway was recognizing the severe class imbalance in the dataset, where images
with helmets heavily outnumbered those without. This imbalance taught me that relying solely on overall accuracy can be a dangerous metric in safety-critical application
s, as a model might perform poorly at detecting violations while maintaining a deceptively high accuracy score. To mitigate this, I learned how evaluating precision and 
recall becomes essential, discovering that lowering the prediction confidence threshold to a range of 0.3 to 0.4 is a much smarter business strategy. In a hazardous
workplace, missing a single safety violation is far more dangerous than triggering a false alarm. Ultimately, this project taught me how to transform raw industrial
imagery into a clean, well-structured dataset prepared for advanced neural networks, providing a practical foundation for deploying real-time automated safety alerts
directly into manufacturing and construction site camera feeds.

### Medical Assistant: Generative AI RAG Solution

In this project, I learned how to build a smart, context-aware question-answering system that uses large language models to answer queries based on internal company 
documents. I started by understanding how raw, unstructured text files are processed into a format that a machine learning pipeline can use. I learned how to clean text
by removing unnecessary white space and characters, and how to split long documents into smaller, meaningful text chunks. This chunking process is vital because it
ensures the language model only receives highly relevant pieces of information rather than being overwhelmed by a massive document all at once. From there, I learned
how to convert these text chunks into mathematical vectors, known as embeddings, using pre-trained models. These embeddings capture the actual meaning and context of 
the words, which allowed me to store them in a specialized vector database. I discovered that a vector database works by calculating the mathematical similarity between
a user's question and the stored document text, quickly retrieving the top matching pieces of text that contain the answer. Moving into the model development phase, I 
gained practical experience working with large language models through APIs and configuring essential parameters like temperature, top-p, and token limits to control how
creative or precise the system's answers are. I learned how to engineer custom system prompts that instruct the model to behave like a helpful customer support agent and
, crucially, to only answer using the provided document text rather than making things up. By combining the vector database search with the generation power of the language
model, I built a complete system where a user asks a question, the database retrieves the most relevant paragraph from the company manual, and the language model reads
that paragraph to write a clean, natural response. Finally, I learned how to build an interactive, web-based user interface using Streamlit, which allowed me to deploy
the model into a clean dashboard where anyone can type a question, see the chat history, and get instant answers. Ultimately, this project taught me how to bridge the
gap between static documents and artificial intelligence, turning raw data into a real-time, trustworthy AI assistant that can automate customer support and dramatically
reduce the time humans spend answering repetitive questions.

### ReneWind: Predictive Maintenance Optimization

Through the ReneWind predictive maintenance project, I learned how to use sensor data and machine learning to predict mechanical failures in wind turbine generators 
before they happen. I worked with a large dataset containing 20,000 records across 40 different hidden sensor features. While looking over the data, my initial checks 
found a small number of missing values (18 empty entries each in the first two sensor columns), which taught me the importance of scanning for missing details before 
starting a project. I also discovered that the data had already been scaled and centered around zero, meaning it was clean and pre-processed for mathematical consistency
, though certain sensor columns still showed highly volatile ranges that pointed to potential machine anomalies. A major challenge in this project was dealing with a 
massive class imbalance: 94.45% of the data represented normal turbine operations, while only 5.55% captured actual generator failures. This taught me that evaluating a 
model based only on its overall accuracy is highly misleading, as a model could simply guess "no failure" every time and still score over 94% while completely missing 
actual breakdowns. Because missing a failure (a False Negative) is incredibly expensive due to replacement costs, I learned how to prioritize high-recall models and 
adjust decision boundaries. This project showed me how accepting small inspection costs from occasional false alarms (False Positives) is a much smarter strategy for a
business, as it ultimately saves millions by catching catastrophic wind turbine failures early.

### EasyVisa: Application Processing Automation

Through the EasyVisa machine learning project, I learned how to clean, visualize, and analyze a large dataset to build a predictive model that helps automate the
visa approval process. I started by exploring a dataset of 25,480 visa application records across 12 distinct employer and employee characteristics. While the dataset
had no missing values, my initial data quality check caught critical errors, such as negative numbers for a company's total employee count, which required fixing before
any modeling could begin. By running statistical summaries, I discovered a massive range in company sizes—with the largest reaching over 600,000 employees—and wide
differences in prevailing wages, showing that the data needed to be scaled properly so the large numbers wouldn't confuse the machine learning model. When creating 
charts to understand the data, I discovered a major class imbalance: roughly 66.8% of historical applications were "Certified" (approved) while only 33.2% were "Denied".
This taught me that relying purely on simple accuracy wouldn't be enough to judge a model's true performance, as it would be biased toward the majority class. Through 
further visual analysis, I found that an applicant's education level (like holding a Master's degree), prior job experience, and the region of employment played massive
roles in whether a visa was approved. Ultimately, this project taught me how to take raw applicant and employer data, clean out outliers, and turn it into a smart 
classification system that reduces manual paperwork, speeds up decision-making, and helps an organization focus its review efforts efficiently.

### Personal Loan Campaign: Target Customer Segmentation

Through this personal loan project, I learned how to clean, analyze, and map out bank customer data to make marketing campaigns much more efficient. I started with a
dataset of 5,000 customers across 14 different features. A quick data quality check showed that the data was very clean with no missing numbers or duplicate rows, using
13 integer columns and one decimal column to track credit card spending. By checking the unique values, I confirmed that key features like bank account usage were simple
yes-or-no categories. However, the statistical summary caught an error: the job experience column listed a minimum value of -3 years, which is a mistake that needs to be
fixed before building any machine learning models. I also found important averages for the bank's customer base: the average age was around 45 years, the average annual
income was $73.77K (ranging up to $224K), and average credit card spending was $1.94K per month. Most importantly, I calculated that only 9.6% of targeted customers
actually accepted a loan offer in the past. This heavy imbalance taught me that simple accuracy is a bad way to judge success, and I need to focus on precision and
recall instead. Using Python charting tools, I found that customer ages follow a standard bell curve centered between 30 and 50, while incomes are right-skewed, 
meaning most people make middle-to-lower incomes but a few high-earning outliers pull up the average. Ultimately, I used these patterns to group customers, discovering 
that middle-aged, high-earning professionals who use online banking and already hold investment or savings accounts are the most likely to say yes to a loan, allowing 
the bank to focus its marketing budget exactly where it works best.

### FoodHub: Logistics and Aggregator Optimization

Through this food delivery data analysis project, I learned how to clean, structure, and explore real-world datasets to find important business insights. I started
by checking the data files to see exactly how much information I had to work with. My dataset contained 1,898 total order records split across 9 different columns,
which included numerical information like whole numbers and decimals, as well as categorical information written as text. When I ran an automatic check for missing data,
the system told me there were zero empty slots. However, when I looked closer at the actual text, I found a hidden issue: a large group of 736 orders had customer
ratings listed as the text "Not given" instead of being left completely blank. Finding this hidden gap was a major learning experience because it taught me that
datasets can look perfectly clean on the surface while still hiding incomplete information that needs to be fixed before making final business decisions. Next, I used
basic math summaries to find the standard baseline numbers for how the delivery platform runs day-to-day, discovering that the time it takes for a kitchen to prepare
a meal ranges from a quick minimum of 20 minutes to a maximum of 35 minutes, with the exact average sitting right at 27.37 minutes. To understand these numbers better,
I used Python tools to create charts and graphs. I made matching pairs of histograms and boxplots for different columns, which visually showed me how spread out the
order costs and delivery times were. These specific boxplots were incredibly helpful because they pointed out statistical outliers—orders that took way too long or
cost an unusual amount of money compared to the rest of the data. I also built horizontal bar charts to rank the most popular choices on the app, making it easy to see
which specific restaurants were completing the most orders, which types of food were the most popular, and how customer ordering habits changed between regular weekdays
and busy weekends. Finally, I learned how to split the total delivery process into two separate parts: the time the restaurant takes to cook the food, and the time the
courier takes to travel to the customer's house. By breaking the numbers down this way, I learned how to turn raw spreadsheet data into smart operational strategies to
help dispatch delivery riders more efficiently, fix traffic bottlenecks, keep food arriving hot, and ultimately help local restaurant partners grow.
